      <description><![CDATA[Visit http://archive.nextanimationstudio.com or contact inquiries@nextanimation.com.tw to license this or any News Direct videoFor story suggestions please contact tips@nextanimation.com.twRESTRICTIONS: NONEA report by CNN claims that Russian-linked election influencers attempted to sway American politics last summer through the mobile game Pokémon Go.CNN reports that they found a word of Russian metadata in a four-page Microsoft Word document sent by email.  That document, CNN says, was part of an email exchange between a writer and a person called Daniel Reed, the Chief Editor of Do Not Shoot Us.DoNotShoot.Us reportedly posed as part of the Black Lives Matter movement, covering stories of police brutality.However, CNN reported that the website’s Facebook page was one of many accounts shut down by Facebook after the social network linked them to a Russian business called the Internet Research Agency. That business is said to conduct influence operations on behalf of the Kremlin.CNN speculates that Don’t Shoot Us was set up to stoke racial tensions between the black community and the rest of America. The news network claims that in the summer 2016, a Do Not Shoot Us Tumblr page asked users to play mobile monster-catching game Pokémon Go in places where police brutality took place.Users were encouraged to catch a Pokémon, name it after a victim of police brutality and send a screenshot of it to Do Not Shoot Us as part of Amazon gift card contest by email.CNN says the email address provided was the same one Reed used to send the aforementioned writer the email that had a file with Russian metadata attached. The news network found no evidence that anyone took part in the contest.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Depiction of Russian metadata being found inside document2. Depiction of Facebook closing accounts3. Depiction of Pokémon Go contest instructions4. Overview of situationVOICEOVER (in English):  “CNN says they found a word of Russian metadata in a four-page Microsoft Word document sent by email. “That document, CNN says, was part of an email exchange between a writer and a person called Daniel Reed, the Chief Editor of Do Not Shoot Us.”“CNN says that website’s Facebook page was one of many accounts shut down by Facebook after the social network linked them to a Russian business called the Internet Research Agency.”“That business is said to conduct influence operations on behalf of the Kremlin.” “CNN claims that in the summer 2016, a Do Not Shoot Us Tumblr page asked users to play mobile monster-catching game Pokémon Go in places where police brutality took place.“Users were encouraged to catch a Pokémon, name it after a victim of police brutality and email a screenshot of it to Do Not Shoot Us as part of an Amazon gift card contest.”“CNN says the email address provided was the same one Reed used to send the aforementioned writer the email that contained a file with Russian metadata attached.”“The news network found no evidence that anyone took part in the contest.”SOURCES: CNNhttp://money.cnn.com/2017/10/12/media/dont-shoot-us-russia-pokemon-go/index.html***For story suggestions please contact tips@nextanimation.com.twFor technical and editorial support, please contact:Asia: +61 2 93 73 1841Europe: +44 20 7542 7599Americas and Latam: +1 800 738 8377]]></description>
