      <title>Moon cave discovery stokes hope for lunar exploration</title>
      <description><![CDATA[Visit http://archive.nextanimationstudio.com or contact inquiries@nextanimation.com.tw to license this or any News Direct videoFor story suggestions please contact tips@nextanimation.com.twRESTRICTIONS: NONEA cavernous lava tube was this week confirmed to exist beneath the surface of the moon. The discovery was after by a team of Japanese and American scientists using data from the SELENE and GRAIL spacecraft to acoustically map the enormous lava tube.These tubes are volcanic underground passages formed by flowing lava to funnel the substance. Once the flow stops, the tube remains with features similar to a cave.The chasm is around 100 meters wide and 50 kilometers long, reported the Guardian. It is located in the Marius Hills region of the celestial body.The cave could provide shelter to astronauts during moon missions, protecting them from dangerous cosmic radiation. This could potentially allow for the development of a lunar exploration base.Details of the finding was published in the journal, Geophysical Research Letters.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Depiction of the chasm2. Explanation of lava tubes3. Depiction of spacecraft mapping cave4. Size and location of lava tube5. Depiction of lunar astronauts inside the lava tube6. Depiction of lunar exploration baseVOICEOVER (in English): "A large and cavernous lava tube was this week confirmed to exist beneath the surface of the moon. "These tubes are volcanic underground passages formed by flowing lava to funnel the substance. "Once the flow stops, the tube remains with features similar to a cave." "The discovery was after by a team of Japanese and American scientists using data from the SELENE and GRAIL spacecraft to acoustically map the enormous lava tube.""The chasm is around 100 meters wide and 50 kilometers long and located in the Marius Hills region of the celestial body." "It could provide shelter to astronauts during moon missions, protecting them from dangerous cosmic radiation.""This could potentially allow for the development of a lunar exploration base."SOURCES: Geophysical Research Letters, Asahi Shimbun, The Guardian, Space.com http://agupubs.onlinelibrary.wiley.com/hub/article/10.1002/2017GL074998/editor-highlight/http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1002/2017GL074998/fullhttp://www.asahi.com/ajw/articles/AJ201710180045.htmlhttps://www.theguardian.com/science/2017/oct/19/lunar-cave-discovery-raises-hopes-for-human-colonisation-of-moonhttps://www.space.com/26592-manned-moon-exploration-lunar-pits.html***For story suggestions please contact tips@nextanimation.com.twFor technical and editorial support, please contact:Asia: +61 2 93 73 1841Europe: +44 20 7542 7599Americas and Latam: +1 800 738 8377]]></description>
