      <title>Broken heart syndrome explained</title>
      <description><![CDATA[Visit http://archive.nextanimationstudio.com or contact inquiries@nextanimation.com.tw to license this or any News Direct videoFor story suggestions please contact tips@nextanimation.com.twRESTRICTIONS: NONEA new study details the case of a Texan woman who was left hospitalized with broken heart syndrome after the death of her dog.The study was published in the New England Journal of Medicine.Also known as Takotsubo cardiomyopathy, broken-heart syndrome sees severe weakening of the heart's left ventricle after a stressful event.This pot like shape is where the condition's name comes from. A takotsubo is a Japanese pot used to trap octopuses.According to Harvard Health, experts believe the sheer amount of adrenaline and hormones triggered by the stressful event may temporarily stupefy the heart.Several tests are required to identify the condition as electrocardiogram readings of it are usually identical to a heart attack. Most doctors prescribe heart failure drugs to help with it. RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. What happens to the heart during broken heart syndrome2. Depiction of woman suffering from broken heart syndrome 3. Depiction of patient in hospital with doctor4..Depiction of statistics of broken heart syndromeVOICEOVER (in English): "Also known as Takotsubo cardiomyopathy, broken-heart syndrome sees severe weakening of the heart's left ventricle after a stressful event.""Experts believe the sheer amount of adrenaline and hormones triggered by the stressful event may temporarily stupefy the heart.""Symptoms involve a shortness of breath and chest pain.""Several tests are required to identify the condition as electrocardiogram readings of it are usually identical to a heart attack.""Most doctors prescribe heart failure drugs to help.""The condition affects vastly more women than men, and around 1 in 5 of those suffering the condition die from it."SOURCES: New England Journal of Medicine, New York Daily News, Harvard Healthhttp://www.nejm.org/doi/full/10.1056/NEJMicm1615835#t=articlehttp://nydn.us/2yZrpvShttps://www.health.harvard.edu/heart-health/takotsubo-cardiomyopathy-broken-heart-syndrome***For story suggestions please contact tips@nextanimation.com.twFor technical and editorial support, please contact:Asia: +61 2 93 73 1841Europe: +44 20 7542 7599Americas and Latam: +1 800 738 8377]]></description>
